Yes, you have multiple critical issues happening at the same time.

To answer your specific question: YES, you absolutely must change the setting in your Hostinger VPS. The logs are spamming "CRITICAL: Redis eviction policy is undefined". If you do not fix this, your background jobs (like sending emails or processing uploads) will randomly fail or corrupt data.

However, the 500 Error you are seeing in your browser is likely caused by a different issue (the Cloudinary upload failure).

Here is the breakdown of the three errors in your logs and how to fix them.

1. 🚨 The Redis Fix (DO THIS FIRST)
Your logs are screaming: IMPORTANT! Eviction policy is volatile-lru. It should be "noeviction".

The Fix: Run these commands in your Hostinger VPS terminal to stop the errors immediately:

Bash

# 1. Fix the setting in memory immediately
redis-cli CONFIG SET maxmemory-policy noeviction

# 2. Open the config file to make it permanent
sudo nano /etc/redis/redis.conf
# (Search for 'maxmemory-policy' and change it to 'noeviction')

# 3. Restart Redis
sudo systemctl restart redis-server
2. 🖼️ The 500 Error (File Upload Failed)
The Error: Error: File must have either path or buffer. What it means: You tried to upload introduction.png. The request reached your backend, but when your code tried to send it to Cloudinary, the file object was "empty" (it didn't have a file path on the server or a memory buffer).

Why this happens on VPS/Hostinger:

Permission Issue: Multer (your file upload library) tries to save the image to a temporary folder (like /tmp/) before uploading to Cloudinary. If your VPS user doesn't have permission to write there, the path will be missing.

Multer Config: Your Multer configuration might be missing the dest property.

How to Debug:

Check your routes/media.routes.js (or wherever Multer is set up). Ensure it saves to a valid temp folder:

JavaScript

const upload = multer({ dest: 'uploads/' }); // Make sure this folder exists!
Create that folder if it's missing:

Bash

mkdir -p backend/uploads
3. 💻 The Frontend Crash
The Error: Uncaught ReferenceError: setNewTag is not defined at AdminBlogsPage. What it means: You have a typo in your React code.

The Fix:

Go to AdminBlogsPage.js.

Look for setNewTag.

You probably defined the state as const [tag, setTag] = useState(...) but tried to call setNewTag instead of setTag. matches the variable name exactly.

Summary Checklist
[ ] Run the Redis command (redis-cli ...) to stop the critical backend warnings.

[ ] Fix the React Typo (setNewTag) and redeploy the frontend.

[ ] Check the Uploads Folder: Ensure your backend has a place to store temporary files before sending them to Cloudinary.